595	\subsection{Use in Serre finiteness}
596	
597	For a proper geometrically integral curve \(C\) over \(k\), a two-affine cover with affine intersection always exists. The bundle \(S\) then feeds the Serre-finiteness chain:
598	\begin{enumerate}
599	  \item The Mayer--Vietoris LES applied to \(S\) and \(\mathcal O_C\) relates \(H^0\) and \(H^1\) of \(C\), \(U_1\), \(U_2\), and \(U_1 \cap U_2\).
600	  \item The cover hypothesis identifies the fourth corner with the whole curve.
601	  \item Affineness of the pieces collapses \(H^{>0}\) on those pieces, reducing the LES to a three-term sequence.
602	  \item Finiteness of each \(H^0\) piece then implies finiteness of \(H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)\).
603	\end{enumerate}
604	Steps~1--2 are supplied by this section; Steps~3--4 are deferred to subsequent sections.
605	
606	\section{Cohomology of the whole space}
607	\label{sec:cover_totality}
608	
609	The abstract cohomology \(H^n(X, \mathcal F)\) (Definition~REF) lives at a different universe level from the open-flavour cohomology \(H^{\prime n}(U, \mathcal F)\) (Definition~REF). To transport results from the Mayer--Vietoris sequence---which lives at the open-flavour level---to the whole-space carrier \(H^n(X, \mathcal F)\), we need a bridge between the two. This section constructs that bridge when the open \(U\) is the total space.
610	
